What you’re noticing (clean version)

In conflicts, people often:
	•	study the opponent deeply
	•	predict their moves
	•	understand their incentives

That requires a form of:

cognitive empathy (seeing from their perspective)

And yes—doing that repeatedly can change how you see them.

⸻

But it’s not quite “empathy makes you like them”

There are actually three different effects that can look similar:

⸻

1. Perspective-taking (cognitive empathy)

You model:
	•	how they think
	•	what they want
	•	how they’ll act

This improves performance in conflict.

But:

you don’t have to like them to do this well.

⸻

2. Familiarity → reduced hostility

The more you:
	•	observe someone
	•	understand their patterns

The less “alien” they feel.

That can soften:
	•	fear
	•	demonization

⸻

3. Identification / assimilation (the risky one)

Sometimes people:
	•	start adopting the opponent’s logic
	•	justify their behavior
	•	blur boundaries

This is closer to what you’re describing as “going native.”

⸻

Why it happens

When you repeatedly do:

“If I were them, what would I do?”

Your brain builds:
	•	internal models
	•	simulated perspectives

Over time:
	•	those models feel more “real”
	•	and less “other”

⸻

But here’s the key distinction

Understanding ≠ agreeing ≠ becoming

High-level operators can:
	•	understand deeply
	•	predict accurately
	•	without adopting or identifying

⸻

The real skill

The optimal state is:

High empathy, strong boundaries

Meaning:
	•	You can step into their perspective
	•	Then step back out cleanly

⸻

